00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:20.550
But that's not always the case.

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:25.570
So, the structure of Breath
of Life, or the goal is

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:29.780
to familiarize participants with
the archives and provide them

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:33.570
with the skills to be able to
find materials on their languages.

00:15:33.570 --> 00:15:37.610 position:56%
We teach fundamentals in linguistics
so that they can begin to read

00:15:37.610 --> 00:15:39.510
and interpret the materials.

00:15:39.510 --> 00:15:41.030
And anyone who's ever looked

00:15:41.030 --> 00:15:44.450
at a manuscript knows
that it's not very easy.

00:15:44.450 --> 00:15:47.520
There are idiosyncrasies
in the documentation,

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:49.440
there's handwriting quirks,

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:53.450
and you need to interpret what's
a noun, what's a verb etcetera.

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:58.600
So, we provide fundamental, you
know basics to be able to do that.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:04.760 position:56%
And, we discuss and demonstrate ways
that the materials can be utilized

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:07.930
for language revitalization
and we always have people

00:16:07.930 --> 00:16:10.730
like Darrell Baldwin
and other people

00:16:10.730 --> 00:16:15.680
who have very similarly
long-standing projects

00:16:15.680 --> 00:16:20.270
in revitalization that come
and share their experience.

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:22.570
So, again there are
three core elements.

00:16:22.570 --> 00:16:28.240
Basic linguistics, archival
research and applied approaches.

00:16:28.240 --> 00:16:33.460
So, Breath of Life, unlike Berkeley
and other Breath of Life models

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.980
that only last a week, the National
Breath of Life takes two weeks,

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:40.490
because again of the
amount of materials

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:42.140
that can be consulted here.

00:16:42.140 --> 00:16:46.610
During that time, the
participants who are selected,

00:16:46.610 --> 00:16:52.140
it's a real competitive
process as well.

00:16:52.140 --> 00:16:54.810
This year we received
around 70 applications.

00:16:54.810 --> 00:17:00.490
And we'll be able to
hose about 30 of them.

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:03.890
So, every language group,

00:17:03.890 --> 00:17:08.020 position:56%
and sometimes we get one single
individual, but generally we get two

00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:10.660
or three people form
one language community

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.400
who come and work together.

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:17.320
And each language group will get
an academically trained linguist

00:17:17.320 --> 00:17:21.560
assigned to work with them one
on one throughout the two weeks.

00:17:21.560 --> 00:17:25.440
On our end, the curators,
the archivists,

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:28.980
the librarians will teach
the participants how

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:31.240
to navigate the catalogs.

00:17:31.240 --> 00:17:33.490
Every institution has a
different type of catalog,

00:17:33.490 --> 00:17:35.210
but overall the principles

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:39.670
of catalog research are
applicable across the board.

00:17:39.670 --> 00:17:43.420
So, we try to make sure that
when the participants leave,

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:46.720
they can still come back to
the catalog and find stuff

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:49.330
that they might be interested in.

00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:51.290
We, of course provide
access to the materials.

00:17:51.290 --> 00:17:55.230
So, ahead of time we pull up
everything for this language

00:17:55.230 --> 00:17:58.570
and that language, and the
participants are able to work

00:17:58.570 --> 00:18:00.660
on the materials hands on.

00:18:00.660 --> 00:18:04.770
And we also produce
archival quality materials.

00:18:04.770 --> 00:18:08.170
We were just actually
talking about trying

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:13.900
to make a more concerted effort
to inform the Library of Congress

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:17.260
about the languages that will be
represented in the next Breath

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:22.170
of Life, which by the way happens
May 29th to June 9th in 2017.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:24.950
And that way the participants
can leave

00:18:24.950 --> 00:18:32.160
with archival surrogates
of their materials.

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:40.320 position:56%
So, Breath of Life national model
has evolved over the last few years.

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:48.000 position:56%
We're going to have again the fourth
iteration in May 2017 for two weeks.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.430
To date, so if you look at the
number languages that we've had

00:18:52.430 --> 00:18:59.110
over the year, 22 was really a
lot of languages; 14, 15 is more

00:18:59.110 --> 00:19:02.270
or less the scope that is
manageable and we can attend

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:06.240
to everyone's needs more
effectively and efficiently.

00:19:06.240 --> 00:19:12.760
So, by the end of 2017 institute
we will have served about 70

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:15.540
or so language communities.

00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:17.650
Every time provide
digital surrogates,

00:19:17.650 --> 00:19:21.650
providing instruction,
access to the materials.

00:19:21.650 --> 00:19:24.190
Now, we're trying to evolve,

00:19:24.190 --> 00:19:29.800
because you know yes we could
keep doing this every 2 years

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:35.090
if the NSF documenting endangered
languages program is willing

00:19:35.090 --> 00:19:36.830
to continue to fund us.

00:19:36.830 --> 00:19:41.320
But we see a need to
evolve in a couple of ways.

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:44.580
First of all, one thing we're
doing this year is we're doing an

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:47.030
assessment of the program
to make sure

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:51.210 position:56%
that indeed participants leave
knowing that they can always go back

00:19:51.210 --> 00:19:53.410
to the catalogs and they
know how to use them.

00:19:53.410 --> 00:19:58.710
That's something we haven't
been able to measure easily

00:19:58.710 --> 00:20:01.670
without a structure to do so.

00:20:01.670 --> 00:20:04.250
A person dedicated to
following up, and so on.

00:20:04.250 --> 00:20:06.470
So, we're going be doing that
assessment of the program,

00:20:06.470 --> 00:20:10.370
not of the participants, but
of our program this year.

00:20:10.370 --> 00:20:14.910
The other thing we are doing
also based on the experience,

00:20:14.910 --> 00:20:20.740
of serving the experiences of these
researchers, is that we've come

00:20:20.740 --> 00:20:26.410
to the realization that we're
asking these researchers to develop

00:20:26.410 --> 00:20:31.430 position:56%
in two weeks the ability to research
catalogs, the ability to carry

00:20:31.430 --> 00:20:33.920
out linguistic analysis
and the ability

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:36.760
to develop an implied
linguistics and pedagogy,

00:20:36.760 --> 00:20:39.800
or language teaching approach.

00:20:39.800 --> 00:20:42.200
All of that in two weeks.

00:20:42.200 --> 00:20:47.490
So, that's a tremendous demand on
these researchers and we're trying

00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:51.610
to figure out how to facilitate at
least a part that we know how to do

00:20:51.610 --> 00:20:55.280
as curators, and archivist,
and library scientist.

00:20:55.280 --> 00:21:01.910
So, in collaboration
with Miami University,

00:21:01.910 --> 00:21:04.860
we are taking this tool MIDA,

00:21:04.860 --> 00:21:07.860
which is the Miami-Illinois
Digital Archives developed

00:21:07.860 --> 00:21:13.260
by the Myaami tribe and apply
it, or make it available

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:16.440
to Breath of Life participants.

00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:21.490
What this tool does is it allows
you to upload digital surrogates,

00:21:21.490 --> 00:21:24.710
high-quality archival tips.

00:21:24.710 --> 00:21:29.160
You're able to code the
type of document that it is,

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:32.860
transcribe the language material.

00:21:32.860 --> 00:21:37.860
Translate it, gloss it, do whatever
level of analysis you need to do

00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:42.700
and it also allows you to
output data from this analysis.

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:47.510
So, the Myaami tribe is using
it to develop a dictionary,

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:50.330
which they don't yet have.

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:53.580
But when I learned about this
tool, which was developed through

00:21:53.580 --> 00:21:59.270
and NEH grant, I figured that we
could tweak it to make it available

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:06.360
to any community that is ready,
that has the human resources

00:22:06.360 --> 00:22:09.890
and an interest to do that kind
of work on their own language.

00:22:09.890 --> 00:22:13.040
So, we're planning to do a pilot
this summer during the Breath

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:17.600
of Life weeks to test it out,
we'll work with one community

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:19.680
that precisely had that experience.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:21.440
We were able to digitize everything

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:24.130
on their language,
deliver it to them.

00:22:24.130 --> 00:22:28.550
We thought, we were very proud and
then they were very overwhelmed.

00:22:28.550 --> 00:22:34.520
So, now we're to work through
the materials with this tool

00:22:34.520 --> 00:22:41.140
and see how we can make it usable
within the Breath of Life context.

