00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:41.100
I'm going to talk about the
work that I've been doing

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:43.960 position:56%
to document the lexicon of Diidxaza,

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:47.690
which is Zapotec language
spoken in the south of Mexico.

00:23:47.690 --> 00:23:52.790
It's spoken by about 70,000
speakers, which sounds like a lot,

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:56.510
but in reality, of
the 22 municipalities

00:23:56.510 --> 00:23:59.920
where the language is
spoken, only or two have kids

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:01.220
that are learning the language.

00:24:01.220 --> 00:24:05.270
So, at this point, in the
community that I work the most,

00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:08.100
the youngest speakers are
in their late 20s already.

00:24:08.100 --> 00:24:15.540
So, in devising a dictionary
for this I came upon; so,

00:24:15.540 --> 00:24:19.200
this is a dictionary with
well over 10,000 entries.

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:21.460
Now it's about 13,000.

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:24.510
About 1000 of those entries
were related to plants.

00:24:24.510 --> 00:24:28.420
And I had crazy entries
like the one I have here.

00:24:28.420 --> 00:24:34.960 position:56%
Where a tree would be called
[foreign words], so different names.

00:24:34.960 --> 00:24:40.100 position:56%
They would give me different names
in Spanish for the for this one word

00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:43.130
in Zapotec [foreign words].

00:24:43.130 --> 00:24:48.130
And the descriptions I
had were all over the map.

00:24:48.130 --> 00:24:53.870
It's you know sometimes I would
be told that the tree exfoliates,

00:24:53.870 --> 00:24:55.290
sometimes it doesn't exfoliate.

00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:56.590
Sometimes it has latex.

00:24:56.590 --> 00:24:58.350
Sometimes it has sap.

00:24:58.350 --> 00:25:00.070
Sometimes it has medicinal uses.

00:25:00.070 --> 00:25:01.550
Sometimes it doesn't.

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:06.840
And that made me realize that the
documentation I had collected,

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:11.200
this was in 2010, was just not
going to give me the documentation

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:13.710
that would be adequate
for a dictionary.

00:25:13.710 --> 00:25:15.990
So, because I was already at
the Museum of Natural History,

00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:17.900
I start talking to botanists.

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:21.290
I ran a pilot in 2012
to try to figure out how

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:23.990
to conduct botanical research,

00:25:23.990 --> 00:25:27.880
which is something I did not
learn in linguistics school.

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:30.510
And, to make a long story short,

00:25:30.510 --> 00:25:34.880
we carried out a one-year
plant documentation project,

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:38.960
interdisciplinary looking
at documenting the plants

00:25:38.960 --> 00:25:41.200
with two botanists in the project.

00:25:41.200 --> 00:25:44.500
Documenting knowledge with
several knowledge bearers

00:25:44.500 --> 00:25:49.620
from the community, taking
audio, taking photographs

00:25:49.620 --> 00:25:52.130
by a professional photographer.

00:25:52.130 --> 00:25:56.570
And in the end, we ended
up with a huge database

00:25:56.570 --> 00:25:59.460
which we're tweaking, even today.

00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:02.970
We did 92 field collection sights.

00:26:02.970 --> 00:26:06.040
Lots of numbers that I
don't need to bore you with.

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:11.230 position:56%
But we ended up with a collection; a
huge collection of botanical samples

00:26:11.230 --> 00:26:14.360
like the one you can see there,
housed at the National Museum

00:26:14.360 --> 00:26:18.070
of National History, at the
National Herbarium in Mexico,

00:26:18.070 --> 00:26:21.090
and two herbaria in [inaudible],

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:24.760
in the state where the
community is located.

00:26:24.760 --> 00:26:27.950
And we have over 5000 high-quality,

00:26:27.950 --> 00:26:31.280
high resolution images
of the plants.

00:26:31.280 --> 00:26:33.840
So, with that we were
able to clean things up.

00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:38.420
And I learned that there's an
entire, sort of the equivalent

00:26:38.420 --> 00:26:42.320
of a genus of [foreign word] trees.

00:26:42.320 --> 00:26:44.580
And indeed, they have
very different properties

00:26:44.580 --> 00:26:47.330
because they're very
different species.

00:26:47.330 --> 00:26:49.140
They belong to different families.

00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:52.690
So, they're going to look
different and behave differently.

00:26:52.690 --> 00:26:58.110
And now, we have a clear
understanding of why these trees,

00:26:58.110 --> 00:27:00.340
despite their very
different properties,

00:27:00.340 --> 00:27:03.640
are all lumped into
this one category.

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:07.940
And it's the architecture of the
tree that brings them all together.

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:09.760
We did not realize that.

